The-e scholia are not of much assistance in the attempt to restore the words of Horace himself. Often they do not com- ment on the words in dispute and, when they do, Porphyrion often supports one reading, Acron the other. Sometimes, too, one reading is quoted as a heading to a note while the note itself explains the other. No editor has at present found the due to all this tangle. Messrs Keller and Holder, who have examined far more MSS. than anybody else, have divided them into three elaeses, but the grounds on which they base this division are most unsatisfactory.
